                <head>109. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On July 22, <persName corresp="#p_WWA1">William Wieland</persName>, in a
                    memorandum to Assistant Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1"
                        >Rubottom</persName>, recalled the major developments in the U.S.
                    Government’s policy of cutting back on arms shipments to the <persName
                        corresp="#p_BZF1">Batista</persName> government and pointed out that the
                    Military Assistance Advisory Group in Havana had asked the Department of State
                    to approve the sale to Cuba of two items it defined as noncombat equipment. The
                    two items were both aircraft parts, which <persName corresp="#p_WWA1"
                        >Wieland</persName> argued could not be considered as noncombat items. In
                    response to <persName corresp="#p_WWA1">Wieland</persName>’s request for his
                    views, <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1">Rubottom</persName> wrote in the margin:
                    “Agree.”</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_WWA1">Wieland</persName> recommended that the Department
                    approve only those pending items that clearly fell within the definition of
                    “noncombat equipment,” such as a fire truck, a 2½–ton trailer, communications
                    equipment, telescopes, and spare parts for a C–47 cargo aircraft. He emphasized
                    that spare parts for military aircraft should not be approved. <persName
                        corresp="#p_WWA1">Wieland</persName> said that if <persName
                        corresp="#p_RRRJ1">Rubottom</persName> accepted his recommendation, he would
                    take the necessary steps to approve the items for shipment. In the margin
                        <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1">Rubottom</persName> wrote: “Approve. RRR.”
                    (Department of State, Central Files, 737.56/7–2258)</p>
            </div>
